{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RcZXE37fvqEcdRAprQKyYj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The cluster is running on HTTP (not HTTPS) with no authentication. Everything gets 200 regardless of credentials.\n\nThis means:\n1. `xpack.security.enabled` is not set or is false\n2. The cluster accepts any HTTP request without auth\n\nFor the oracle to pass:\n1. The oracle detects scheme: tries https (fails with 000), then tries http (gets 200) → uses http\n2. The oracle checks `es-file-realm-aggregate` contains both `ops-user` and `report-user` in `users` and `users_roles`\n3. The oracle queries `/_cluster/health` as ops-user → gets 200 (any user works since no auth)\n4. The oracle queries `/app-data/_count` as report-user → will this work?\n5. The negative auth check: `report-user:definitely-wrong-password` → will also get 200 → ORACLE FAILS with \"SECURITY NOT ENFORCED\"!\n\nSo I definitely need to enable security. The oracle `check_auth_enforced` will fail if wrong credentials return 2xx. I need to enable xpack.security and the file realm in the ConfigMap, then add the file realm volume.\n\nNow I'm realizing that Elasticsearch 7.x requires transport layer TLS when security is enabled, even if HTTP can stay plaintext. I need to check if there's already an `es-http-tls` secret or if I need to create transport TLS certificates as well.\n\nThe precondition logs show that `es_env_ready` was skipped because the pods were already running from the previous stage, which means the TLS secret was never created. The oracle can detect the scheme and fall back to HTTP if HTTPS isn't available, but the real constraint is whether I can enable security with just HTTP and no HTTPS. In Elasticsearch 7.x, I'd need to configure transport SSL separately with keystore and truststore paths, which requires certificates I don't currently have.\n\nLooking at what happens when `es_env_ready` runs from scratch—it crea